00:04:53.230 --> 00:04:57.290
I was born in Orange County and
my father was in the military.

00:04:57.290 --> 00:04:59.950
He didn't shoot guns
as part of his service.

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:04.510
He was a navigator in P-3
Orions during the Vietnam War.

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:06.850
But the military
was his introduction

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:09.660
to firearms during
basic training.

00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:13.270
And so when he taught
me how to shoot,

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:17.690
that was a very formative
experience for me.

00:05:17.690 --> 00:05:19.510
I was six years old.

00:05:19.510 --> 00:05:21.520
He taught me the
safety fundamentals

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:25.060
of how to handle and
operate a firearm.

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:29.770
And so fast forward to when
I was working here at Google,

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:34.550
training for the show, I was
looking at all the resources

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:36.540
that were available to me.

00:05:36.540 --> 00:05:40.910
And at the time, since I didn't
have a lot of gun friends--

00:05:40.910 --> 00:05:42.670
I mean, I had some
gun friends, but I

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:45.770
didn't have a ton of
instructors who could teach me

00:05:45.770 --> 00:05:46.590
all these things.

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:47.923
AUSTIN WILKINS: You lived in OC.

00:05:47.923 --> 00:05:48.860
CHRIS CHENG: Yeah.

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:52.550
was mostly relying on
the internet for advice,

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:56.210
for guidance to
help me understand

00:05:56.210 --> 00:06:00.710
certain tactics, certain
firearms, certain

00:06:00.710 --> 00:06:02.980
marksmanship fundamentals.

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:06.410
And I remember reading
about even something

00:06:06.410 --> 00:06:08.225
as basic as caliber.

00:06:08.225 --> 00:06:09.350
It's like, what is caliber?

00:06:09.350 --> 00:06:11.780
And why are some of
these bullet measurements

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:16.230
in the imperial system, others
are in the metric system?

00:06:16.230 --> 00:06:21.070
And everyone has their way of
explaining certain concepts.

00:06:21.070 --> 00:06:23.630
But "Shoot to Win" is
my way of explaining

00:06:23.630 --> 00:06:28.560
things in the most
simple terms possible.

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:30.380
"Shoot to Win" is
for the layman.

00:06:30.380 --> 00:06:33.410
It's for the beginner,
someone has no idea

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:35.750
about anything about firearms.

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:41.810
Because like with anything
new, if a topic is confusing,

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:43.860
it can be intimidating.

00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:45.880
It can be off-putting
if you start getting,

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:48.200
I don't know, too
technical or too deep

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:50.690
in the weeds about
certain concepts.

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:52.910
And so I wanted to
really just whittle this

00:06:52.910 --> 00:06:54.200
down to the basics.

00:06:54.200 --> 00:07:00.620
And for me, when I think about
firearms, a firearm is a tool.

00:07:00.620 --> 00:07:03.060
There's many, many
tools out there.

00:07:03.060 --> 00:07:05.510
And just like any tool,
once you understand

00:07:05.510 --> 00:07:09.260
how to operate it
safely, naturally, you

00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:12.890
gain confidence in
how to use the tool.

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:15.830
If we need to chop down some
trees, I'm like, hey, Austin.

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:17.008
We need to use a chainsaw.

00:07:17.008 --> 00:07:18.800
And if you've never
used a chainsaw before,

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:20.842
I'm not just going to put
a chainsaw in your hand

00:07:20.842 --> 00:07:22.250
and be like, go to it.

00:07:22.250 --> 00:07:24.500
We would need to talk
about, all right, safety,

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:27.260
handling for the chainsaw, and
how to turn it on and safely

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:28.220
cut wood.

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:32.150
So for me, a firearm is very,
very similar in that regard,

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:37.070
that it's a tool that when
the operator and the user

00:07:37.070 --> 00:07:39.500
how to safely use
it and handle it,

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:42.590
then it becomes more
approachable and usable

00:07:42.590 --> 00:07:44.252
for the average person.

00:07:44.252 --> 00:07:45.710
AUSTIN WILKINS:
Yeah, that's great.

00:07:45.710 --> 00:07:47.930
And I noticed that,
while reading this book,

00:07:47.930 --> 00:07:52.430
it really intrigued me how not
only the book an incredibly

00:07:52.430 --> 00:07:54.390
detailed book
about how to start,

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:56.630
but it also, in
the introduction,

00:07:56.630 --> 00:08:00.470
really went over your philosophy
for how you won Top Shot

00:08:00.470 --> 00:08:03.430
and how to kind of win
at life, in general.

00:08:03.430 --> 00:08:05.660
Can you tell us more
about the philosophies

00:08:05.660 --> 00:08:09.560
that you've implemented when
on the show and in the book?

00:08:09.560 --> 00:08:10.310
CHRIS CHENG: Yeah.

00:08:10.310 --> 00:08:13.640
So as the title
implies, shoot to win.

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:17.210
But for me, it's not just
about shooting to win,

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:18.410
it's about winning in life.

00:08:18.410 --> 00:08:21.950
And a big part of that for
me is my personal philosophy

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:26.580
and attitude towards whatever
it is that I'm working at.

00:08:26.580 --> 00:08:33.350
So for example, when I
was training for the show,

00:08:33.350 --> 00:08:36.440
I was putting in about 50
hours a week, here at Google,

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:38.270
as a normal work week.

00:08:38.270 --> 00:08:41.929
But on top of that, I was
putting in 20 to 25 hours

00:08:41.929 --> 00:08:42.750
a week.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:45.080
I basically was
treating training

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:47.472
like a part-time job on
top of my full-time job.

00:08:47.472 --> 00:08:48.680
AUSTIN WILKINS: That's a lot.

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:51.740
CHRIS CHENG: And
so winning, to me,

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:57.350
requires dedication,
focus, and sacrifice.

00:08:57.350 --> 00:09:00.140
A big part of my training, I
remember sending an email out

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:02.270
to my family and to my friends.

00:09:02.270 --> 00:09:04.230
And I remember
saying to them, hey,

00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:06.710
I'm training for this TV show.

00:09:06.710 --> 00:09:09.672
Most of my friends and family
had no idea what Top Shot was.

00:09:09.672 --> 00:09:11.630
But I told them, hey,
I'm training for the show

00:09:11.630 --> 00:09:12.740
and I want to win.

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:14.450
And in order for
me to win, I need

00:09:14.450 --> 00:09:16.790
to go off the grid
here and just fully

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:20.900
dedicate myself towards
learning as much as I can about

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:24.830
marksmanship, because I knew
how far behind the curve I was.

00:09:24.830 --> 00:09:29.130
Most of the Top Shot
competitors are law enforcement,

00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:35.330
military, Olympics shooting
champions, lifelong hunters,

00:09:35.330 --> 00:09:38.570
people who are like this
is not just a craft,

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:41.880
but it is their life
and their lifestyle.

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:44.450
And then here I am, just
the self-taught amateur

00:09:44.450 --> 00:09:47.690
who occasionally goes to
the range on weekends.

00:09:47.690 --> 00:09:49.680
So I really needed to catch up.

00:09:49.680 --> 00:09:52.580
And I told my
friends and family,

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:54.650
I appreciate all
the invitations,

00:09:54.650 --> 00:09:57.320
family dinners to
birthday parties.

00:09:57.320 --> 00:10:00.260
But unfortunately, I'm not
going to be able to make it.

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:02.072
I won't be attending.

00:10:02.072 --> 00:10:04.280
After this whole Top Shot
thing is over, though, yes.

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:08.860
I will resume my
regular social life.

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:13.160
So winning requires
sacrifice and hard work.

00:10:13.160 --> 00:10:19.110
And very rarely in life do
things come free or easy.

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:22.130
And that is a big part
of the philosophy.

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:23.960
The philosophical
part of "Shoot to Win"

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:28.860
is that when we talk about
firearms safety and education,

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:32.420
you can't just buy a gun
and expect that it's just

00:10:32.420 --> 00:10:34.790
going to protect you.

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:38.270
The user needs to
train him or herself

00:10:38.270 --> 00:10:41.510
on how to safely
operate and use it.

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:43.190
And then beyond just
the usage, there

00:10:43.190 --> 00:10:46.910
are additional layers
of training and tactics

00:10:46.910 --> 00:10:50.450
around home defense,
personal protection.

00:10:50.450 --> 00:10:52.850
But it does require
effort and time

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:57.560
and sacrifice and dedication
to a craft in order to win.

00:10:57.560 --> 00:11:01.170
And that's not just for
learning how to shoot guns.

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:05.870
It's about the work that
we do in our daily careers.

00:11:05.870 --> 00:11:10.640
It's whatever personal goals
that we set out for ourselves

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:14.630
and that we want to
accomplish in our lives.

00:11:14.630 --> 00:11:18.500
Winning is what makes
us better because it's

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:21.860
that competition
of ideas, and it's

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:24.560
the competition of
people and companies

00:11:24.560 --> 00:11:28.983
that, ultimately, it
makes everything better.

00:11:28.983 --> 00:11:30.858
AUSTIN WILKINS: That's
some heavy philosophy.

00:11:33.550 --> 00:11:36.040
Within that
philosophy, I remember

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:39.040
reading about using
a mental checklist

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:41.800
to keep yourself calm.

00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:45.550
Do you use checklists in
other parts of life as well?

00:11:45.550 --> 00:11:47.050
CHRIS CHENG: Yeah.

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:51.620
So a big part of
"Shoot to Win," for me,

00:11:51.620 --> 00:11:54.760
it was about taking
skills that I

00:11:54.760 --> 00:11:58.210
had developed in
other parts of my life

00:11:58.210 --> 00:12:00.640
and applying that to the show.

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:02.950
And I really have
to credit Google

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:07.000
for a lot of the
skills-based mindset.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.250
When we talk about
personal development plans

